@node sb-fiber
@section sb-fiber
@cindex Fiber
@cindex Sb-fiber

@code{sb-fiber} provides user-space execution contexts -- coroutines
with their own control and binding stacks, cooperatively scheduled and
confined to a single OS thread.

@code{switch-fiber} is the only control-transfer operation;
schedulers, I/O integration, and fiber-aware synchronization live in
user code.

@subsection API

@deffn Function make-fiber function &key name (stack-size 65536) (binding-stack-size 8192)
Create a new fiber whose entry @var{function} runs when first switched
to.  @var{name}, if supplied, is a string label used by
@code{print-object} (mirroring @code{sb-thread:thread-name}).  Returns
a @code{fiber} object that must eventually be passed to
@code{destroy-fiber}.

If @var{function} returns normally, the fiber is marked @code{:dead}
and control auto-switches back to its return fiber, carrying the
return value as the auto-return's value (see @code{switch-fiber}).
If @var{function} exits via an unhandled condition, the condition is
stashed on the fiber and re-signaled in the caller's context on the
auto-return.
@end deffn

@deffn Function make-main-fiber &key name
Create a fiber representing the current thread's own stack and bind
@code{*current-fiber*}.  Must be called once on each thread that
intends to use fibers, and destroyed after that thread is done.
@end deffn

@deffn Function fiber-name fiber
The @code{:name} string supplied to @code{make-fiber}, or @code{nil}.
@end deffn

@deffn Function destroy-fiber fiber
Release @var{fiber}'s stacks.  @var{fiber} must not be running.
@end deffn

@deffn Macro with-fiber (var function &rest make-args) &body body
@code{make-fiber} + @code{unwind-protect} + @code{destroy-fiber}.
@end deffn

@deffn Function switch-fiber from to &optional value
Suspend @var{from} and resume @var{to}, delivering @var{value}.
Returns the value supplied by the next switch-in (or @var{to}'s entry
function's return value if it ran to completion).  Both fibers must
be registered to the current thread; @var{from} must be
@code{:running} and @var{to} must be @code{:runnable} or @code{:new}.

The switch preserves the resumed fiber's control stack, binding stack,
@code{*handler-clusters*}, @code{*restart-clusters*}, current catch
and unwind-protect chains, callee-saved registers, and (on x86-64)
the SSE control word.  @code{*current-fiber*} (per-thread) tracks the
resumed fiber.

If @var{to}'s entry function previously escaped via an unhandled
condition, that condition is re-signaled here in the caller's
context.
@end deffn

@deffn Function yield-fiber &optional value
@code{(switch-fiber *current-fiber* (fiber-return-fiber *current-fiber*) value)}.
Errors if the current fiber has never been resumed.
@end deffn

@deffn Function join-fiber fiber
Resume @var{fiber} from @code{*current-fiber*} repeatedly until its
entry function returns; return that function's value.  Parallels
@code{sb-thread:join-thread} for cooperative coroutines.
@end deffn

@deffn Function interrupt-fiber fiber condition
Stage @var{condition} to be signaled in @var{fiber} on its next
resume.  Cooperative: nothing happens until @code{switch-fiber}
delivers control into @var{fiber}, at which point @var{condition}
is signaled in the fiber's own context (for a runnable fiber) or
raised by the trampoline before the entry function runs (for a new
fiber).  Mirrors @code{sb-thread:interrupt-thread} in shape but not
in preemption semantics.
@end deffn

@deffn Function fiber-condition fiber
The condition (if any) staged for @var{fiber}'s next resume, or
@code{nil}.  Cleared when consumed by @code{switch-fiber}.
@end deffn

@deffn Function make-fiber-generator function &key name
Wrap @var{function} in a fiber and return a thunk that, on each
call, resumes the fiber and returns its next @code{yield-fiber}
value (or the entry function's return value).  Returns @code{nil}
when the fiber has run to completion; the underlying fiber is
auto-destroyed at that point.  Mirrors Lua's @code{coroutine.wrap}.
@end deffn

@deffn Macro do-fiber-generator (var generator) &body body
Iterate @var{var} over the values produced by @var{generator}
(a thunk built by @code{make-fiber-generator}), terminating when
the generator returns @code{nil}.
@end deffn

@deffn Function current-fiber
Function form of @code{*current-fiber*}.
@end deffn

@deffn Macro with-fiber-pinned () &body body
Mark the current fiber unsuspendable for the dynamic extent of
@var{body}; @code{switch-fiber} signals an error if invoked with a
pinned @code{from}.  Pins nest.  Intended for FFI: wrap any region
containing live foreign frames so a yield can't leave them atop a
re-entered stack.
@end deffn

@deffn Function fiber-pinned-p fiber
@code{t} if @var{fiber} has a nonzero pin count.
@end deffn

@deffn Function fiber-alive-p fiber
@code{t} if @var{fiber}'s state is not @code{+fiber-dead+} (i.e. it
has not run to completion or been destroyed).
@end deffn

@deffn Function fiber-state fiber
Integer state: @code{+fiber-new+}, @code{+fiber-runnable+},
@code{+fiber-running+}, @code{+fiber-dead+}.
@end deffn

@subsection Example

@lisp
(require :sb-fiber)
(use-package :sb-fiber)

(let* ((main  (make-main-fiber))
       (child (make-fiber
               (lambda ()
                 (format t "hello from child~%")
                 (yield-fiber)
                 (format t "back again~%")))))
  (switch-fiber main child)
  (format t "main resumed~%")
  (switch-fiber main child)
  (destroy-fiber child)
  (destroy-fiber main))
@end lisp

Prints @code{hello from child}, @code{main resumed}, @code{back again}.

A realistic scheduler layers non-blocking I/O on top: when a fiber
would block on an fd, it registers with
@code{poll}/@code{epoll}/@code{kqueue} and yields; the scheduler's
poll loop wakes it when ready.

@subsection Caveats

@itemize
@item @strong{Platforms.}  x86-64 and arm64 POSIX only.
@item @strong{No migration.}  A fiber is bound to its creating thread.
@item @strong{No preemption.}  Tight compute loops starve the scheduler.
@item @strong{Handler isolation.}  A fiber's entry function runs with
a fresh @code{*handler-clusters*} / @code{*restart-clusters*};
handlers on the caller's stack do not catch conditions raised inside.
Let conditions escape -- they're re-signaled in the caller on the
auto-return.
@item @strong{Image survival.}  Fibers do not survive
@code{save-lisp-and-die}; drop wrapper references before saving.
@end itemize
